HabermanDataset: The dataset contains cases from a study that was conducted between 1958 and 1970 at the University of Chicago's Billings Hospital on the survival of patients who had undergone surgery for breast cancer.

General info to get a clear view:

  • The person typically has around 20-30 axillary lymph nodes(lymph nodes in the armpits).
  • After a breast cancer diagnosis, a doctor may check whether cancer cells have spread to the axillary lymph nodes.This can help confirm the diagnosis and staging of cancer.

Source:
1.https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/gilsousa/habermans-survival-data-set 2.https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/319713#:~:text=Axillary%20lymph%20nodes%20are%20located,20%E2%80%9330%20axillary%20lymph%20nodes.

Objective: The objective is to Analyse the DataSet,and to gather the information through EDA.

  • status: Whether petiont has Survived or Not Survived

By observing the records in given DataSet

  • The average age of petients is 52 years.
  • The Youngest Petient is of 30 years old,whereas Eldest is 83 years old.
  • The survival rate of petients is about 73% (224/305*100=73.44%)

According to above observation the diffrence between above classes is found to be higher. Hence,our DataSet is imbalanced.



Univariate Analysis¶

PDF
If a Function follows continuous Destribution,The PDF(probability Density function) is a probability that a random variable X will take value exactly equal to x(a particular value) In simpler words, PDF is a percetage of data at that point.

CDF
The Cumulative Destribution Function is the probability that a random variable X will take value lesser than equals to x(perticular value). In simpler words,CDF tells the percetage of data lesser than equal to that point(x).

In [9]:
counts,bins=np.histogram(df['age'],bins=18,density=True)
pdf=counts/(sum(counts))
cdf=np.cumsum(pdf)
plt.plot(bins[1:],pdf,label='pdf')
plt.plot(bins[1:],cdf,label='cdf')
plt.xlabel("age")
plt.ylabel("PDF: P(X)=x\nCDF: P(X)<=x")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.3, 0.6))
plt.title("PDF & CDF of age")
plt.show()
print(f"Survived:\n CDF:{cdf} \n BinEdges:{bins} \n\n...\n\n\n\n")

Survived=df['nodes'][df['status']=='Survived']
NotSurvived=df['nodes'][df['status']=='NotSurvived']
counts,bins=np.histogram(Survived,bins=18,density=True)
pdf=counts/(sum(counts))
cdf=np.cumsum(pdf)
plt.plot(bins[1:],pdf,label='S_pdf')
plt.plot(bins[1:],cdf,label='S_cdf')
plt.xlabel("Nodes")
plt.ylabel("PDF: P(X)=x\nCDF: P(X)<=x")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.3, 0.6))
plt.title("The PDF and CDF of nodes for Survived")
plt.show()
print(f"Survived:\n CDF:{cdf} \n BinEdges:{bins} \n\n...\n\n\n\n")
print("\n\n The PDF and CDF of nodes for NotSurvived")
counts1,bins1=np.histogram(NotSurvived,bins=18,density=True)
NSpdf=counts1/(sum(counts1))
NScdf=np.cumsum(NSpdf)
plt.plot(bins1[1:],NSpdf,label='NS_pdf')
plt.plot(bins1[1:],NScdf,label='NS_cdf')
plt.xlabel("Nodes")
plt.ylabel("PDF: P(X)=x\nCDF: P(X)<=x")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.3, 0.6))
plt.title("The PDF and CDF of nodes for NotSurvived")
plt.show()
print(f"NotSurvived:\n CDF:{NScdf} \n BinEdges:{bins1}\n")

In [15]:
#(df['age'][df['status']=='NotSurvived']).min()

For Survived,

  • The box plot with survived has values below 50th percentile all lying on 0,and therefore most of the petients survived have 0 infected nodes.
  • 75th percentile of petients survived have about 3 or 4 infected nodes.
  • The points beyond whiskers are less likely to be outliers because there are more than normal number of them.But the point at 46(i.e,Petient with 46 infected nodes) is an extreme outlier,Because person generally has about 20-30 axillary nodes,person having 46 nodes is not possible.

For NotSurvived,

  • 25th percentile of petients not survived had about 0 or 1 infected nodes.
  • About 50th percentile of petients had infected nodes lesser than or equal to 4(<=: because the median lies on 4.5) and 75th percentile of petients have lesser than equal to 11 infected nodes.
  • The maximum number of infected nodes in petient are 24.(excluding the extreme outliers).

  • Many of petionts have lesser than 10 infected nodes & Most of them have 0 infected nodes.

Insights and Takeaways:¶

  • Through statistial Description:

    1. The Youngest Petient is of 30 years old,whereas Eldest is 83 years old.
    2. The survival rate of petionts is about 73%.

     

  • Through Uni-Variate & Bi-Variate Analysis:

    1. Petient has higher chances of survival if petiont is lesser than 40 year old or petiont has lesser age.
    2. Petient has lesser infected nodes,even better if petiont has lesser than 4 infected nodes.

    3. Most of the surviving petients have 0 infected nodes.

    4. Most of the petients (irrespective of status) have lesser than 11 infected nodes.

    5. Most of petionts(around 50%) are 43 to 63 years old
